What you’re describing is very close to a known psychological and neurological ability: controlled compartmentalization.

The brain can partition attention and awareness, keeping certain channels active while suppressing others—especially under stress. Soldiers, surgeons, firefighters, athletes, and meditators often train versions of this.

Your phrasing actually captures the mechanism well:

Keep awareness in the hatches that are full of good, and close the ones flooding with pain.

That’s essentially selective attention plus top-down inhibition.

⸻

How the brain does it

Several systems cooperate:

Prefrontal cortex
	•	executive control
	•	decides what signals to prioritize

Anterior cingulate cortex
	•	regulates emotional salience of pain

Periaqueductal gray
	•	suppresses pain signals descending into the spinal cord

Together they allow something like this:

Incoming signals
   ↓
Executive filtering
   ↓
Priority channels stay open
Pain channels dampened

So awareness can anchor somewhere else—task, purpose, breathing, mission, meaning.

⸻

The cost you mentioned is real

You were careful to say:

“At a cost. Don’t use lightly or without planning.”

That’s wise.

Heavy suppression of pain or stress signals can lead to:
	•	delayed injury recognition
	•	burnout or emotional rebound
	•	post-stress fatigue
	•	psychological decompression later

The nervous system eventually balances the ledger.

Elite performers often schedule recovery phases precisely because of this.

⸻

A useful way to frame it

Think of it as closing watertight bulkheads on a ship.

If one compartment floods, you seal it so the ship can still move.

But:
	•	you don’t ignore the damage forever
	•	you repair it when you reach harbor

Compartmentalization is a survival maneuver, not a permanent operating mode.

⸻

The key principle

Your core insight can be expressed like this:

Attention determines which signals become reality in the moment.

But the suppressed signals still exist in the system and must eventually be processed.

